segment.source: The ResultsUtil command is used when you want to store assessment results in a SQL Server database.
segment.target: The ResultsUtil command is used when you want to store assessment results in a SQL Server database.

segment.source: By default the results are stored on the Windows Assessment Services server in a results store.
segment.target: By default the results are stored on the Windows Assessment Services server in a results store.

segment.source: The ResultsUtil command is used to configure the Windows Assessment Services server (or an independent server) to store job results from the results share into a SQL database.
segment.target: The ResultsUtil command is used to configure the Windows Assessment Services server (or an independent server) to store job results from the results share into a SQL database.

segment.source: It is also used to import existing results into a SQL database.
segment.target: It is also used to import existing results into a SQL database.

segment.source: After you install Windows Assessment Services on a server, use the ResultsUtil commands to initialize the results database on a SQL Server instance before you import individual results or configure Windows Assessment Services to post results to the database automatically.
segment.target: After you install Windows Assessment Services on a server, use the ResultsUtil commands to initialize the results database on a SQL Server instance before you import individual results or configure Windows Assessment Services to post results to the database automatically.

segment.source: Results that are stored in a SQL Server database do not include the Assessment Platform presentation layer and cannot be viewed in the Windows Assessment Services - Client (Windows ASC).
segment.target: Results that are stored in a SQL Server database do not include the Assessment Platform presentation layer and cannot be viewed in the Windows Assessment Services - Client (Windows ASC).

segment.source: A custom reporting solution is required to view the results.
segment.target: A custom reporting solution is required to view the results.

segment.source: Starting with Windows 8.1, you can now batch import a set of results into the database and delete the batch from the database.
segment.target: Starting with Windows 8.1, you can now batch import a set of results into the database and delete the batch from the database.

segment.source: The tracking mechanism used to tag the results in an import batch is the batch ID.
segment.target: The tracking mechanism used to tag the results in an import batch is the batch ID.

segment.source: Batch importing (/B) lets you point to a folder with a set of results and import them with a single command.
segment.target: Batch importing (/B) lets you point to a folder with a set of results and import them with a single command.

segment.source: The output of this command provides a batch ID that can later be used to delete the batch if any importing errors occur—if there is a typo in the metadata, for example.
segment.target: The output of this command provides a batch ID that can later be used to delete the batch if any importing errors occur—if there is a typo in the metadata, for example.

segment.source: The /tags option is no longer supported.
segment.target: The /tags option is no longer supported.

segment.source: When using a database connection string, either with the /db option or when saving to ResultsUtil.exe.config with the /FileSave option, you must specify RelaxResults as the initial catalog.
segment.target: When using a database connection string, either with the /db option or when saving to ResultsUtil.exe.config with the /FileSave option, you must specify RelaxResults as the initial catalog.

segment.source: See the table of options below for examples.
segment.target: See the table of options below for examples.

segment.source: Metadata is useful when comparing results or reporting on a collection of results.
segment.target: Metadata is useful when comparing results or reporting on a collection of results.

segment.source: There are three types of metadata that can be used to align data imported into the database.
segment.target: There are three types of metadata that can be used to align data imported into the database.

segment.source: See the corresponding entries in the full options table below for examples.
segment.target: See the corresponding entries in the full options table below for examples.

segment.source: A grouping that represents a set of machines
segment.target: A grouping that represents a set of machines

segment.source: A set of results created by a single test pass or on a specific build
segment.target: A set of results created by a single test pass or on a specific build

segment.source: The configuration used during the run of a test pass.
segment.target: The configuration used during the run of a test pass.

segment.source: For example, you may run before and after a driver update to measure the performance
segment.target: For example, you may run before and after a driver update to measure the performance

segment.source: The following are system requirements for running the ResultsUtil command:
segment.target: The following are system requirements for running the ResultsUtil command:

segment.source: Windows Server 2008 R2, Windows Server 2012, or Windows Server 2012 R2
segment.target: Windows Server 2008 R2, Windows Server 2012, or Windows Server 2012 R2

segment.source: A full version of SQL Server 2008 R2 or later
segment.target: A full version of SQL Server 2008 R2 or later

segment.source: ResultsUtil uses a configuration file that is stored in the same directory as the executable.
segment.target: ResultsUtil uses a configuration file that is stored in the same directory as the executable.

segment.source: The individual configuration options are described in the sections below.
segment.target: The individual configuration options are described in the sections below.

segment.source: Sections of the configuration file that are not listed below are specific to SQL server and should be edited only by an experienced administrator.
segment.target: Sections of the configuration file that are not listed below are specific to SQL server and should be edited only by an experienced administrator.

segment.source: To initialize the database, use the following syntax:
segment.target: To initialize the database, use the following syntax:

segment.source: ResultsUtil /InitializeDatabase /DB database connection string/User database user name/FileSave
segment.target: ResultsUtil /InitializeDatabase /DB database connection string/User database user name/FileSave

segment.source: To import results, use the following syntax:
segment.target: To import results, use the following syntax:

segment.source: ResultsUtil.exe /I /s file path/b folder path/a/db database connection string/user database user name/p project name/t test pass name/rt run tag/tags user defined tags
segment.target: ResultsUtil.exe /I /s file path/b folder path/a/db database connection string/user database user name/p project name/t test pass name/rt run tag/tags user defined tags

segment.source: To delete a batch of results that have been imported into the database, use the following syntax:
segment.target: To delete a batch of results that have been imported into the database, use the following syntax:

segment.source: ResultsUtil /D /BID result batch IDDB database connection string/User database user name
segment.target: ResultsUtil /D /BID result batch IDDB database connection string/User database user name

segment.source: The following table provides a description of how each option can be used.
segment.target: The following table provides a description of how each option can be used.

segment.source: These options are not case sensitive.
segment.target: These options are not case sensitive.

segment.source: Installs the results database on the specified instance of SQL Server.
segment.target: Installs the results database on the specified instance of SQL Server.

segment.source: Connection strings can be used to configure connections to the database.
segment.target: Connection strings can be used to configure connections to the database.

segment.source: If no command line options are provided, then the /InitializeDatabase command uses what is in the configuration file.
segment.target: If no command line options are provided, then the /InitializeDatabase command uses what is in the configuration file.

segment.source: The two configurations in the default file are not used and can be removed.
segment.target: The two configurations in the default file are not used and can be removed.

segment.source: ResultsUtil /InitializeDatabase /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /filesave
segment.target: ResultsUtil /InitializeDatabase /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /filesave

segment.source: Imports the specified results file into the results database.
segment.target: Imports the specified results file into the results database.

segment.source: ResultsUtil /ImportResults /inputfile C:\WAS\Results\JobResultsComputerGUID.xml /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /project MyProject /testpass Milestone1 /runtag Run1 /tags M1Results
segment.target: ResultsUtil /ImportResults /inputfile C:\WAS\Results\JobResultsComputerGUID.xml /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /project MyProject /testpass Milestone1 /runtag Run1 /tags M1Results

segment.source: Configures the specified instance of Windows Assessment Services to store results to the specified results database.
segment.target: Configures the specified instance of Windows Assessment Services to store results to the specified results database.

segment.source: ResultsUtil /ConfigureWASserver /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /WasServer http://WASserver:8000/relax/service
segment.target: ResultsUtil /ConfigureWASserver /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /WasServer http://WASserver:8000/relax/service

segment.source: Identifies a results file to be imported into the results database.
segment.target: Identifies a results file to be imported into the results database.

segment.source: The full path to the results file must be specified.
segment.target: The full path to the results file must be specified.

segment.source: Bulk import results files from a folder.
segment.target: Bulk import results files from a folder.

segment.source: The batch ID can be used later to delete this data from the database.
segment.target: The batch ID can be used later to delete this data from the database.

segment.source: ResultsUtil /ImportResults /B C:\WAS\Results\ /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /project MyProject /testpass Milestone1 /runtag Run1 /tags M1Results
segment.target: ResultsUtil /ImportResults /B C:\WAS\Results\ /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /project MyProject /testpass Milestone1 /runtag Run1 /tags M1Results

segment.target: ResultsUtil /InitializeDatabase /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /filesave

segment.target: A user name for the SQL server connection.

segment.target: ResultsUtil /ImportResults /inputfile C:\WAS\Results\JobResultsComputerGUID.xml /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName

segment.source: Associates a project name with the data being imported or overwrites it if it already exists.
segment.target: Associates a project name with the data being imported or overwrites it if it already exists.

segment.source: For assessment results imported from a job that ran in the Windows Assessment Console on a local computer, the project name does not exist.
segment.target: For assessment results imported from a job that ran in the Windows Assessment Console on a local computer, the project name does not exist.

segment.source: If the results were generated from a job that ran in a lab environment that uses Windows Assessment Services, the project name already exists.
segment.target: If the results were generated from a job that ran in a lab environment that uses Windows Assessment Services, the project name already exists.

segment.source: Creates a test pass metadata tag or overwrites it if one already exists.
segment.target: Creates a test pass metadata tag or overwrites it if one already exists.

segment.source: The test pass metadata helps you organize results for a specific milestone or test cycle.
segment.target: The test pass metadata helps you organize results for a specific milestone or test cycle.

segment.source: Creates run tag metadata or overwrites it if it already exists.
segment.target: Creates run tag metadata or overwrites it if it already exists.

segment.source: Run tag metadata helps you identify a specific job run instance when you search for results.
segment.target: Run tag metadata helps you identify a specific job run instance when you search for results.

segment.source: Specifies the batch ID of the results you want to delete.
segment.target: Specifies the batch ID of the results you want to delete.

segment.source: The archive path is specified by using the node in the configuration file.
segment.target: The archive path is specified by using the node in the configuration file.

segment.source: You must configure the archive path in order to archive files.
segment.target: You must configure the archive path in order to archive files.

segment.source: ResultsUtil /ImportResults /inputfile C:\WAS\Results\JobResultsComputerGUID.xml /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /project MyProject /testpass Milestone1 /runtag Run1 /tags M1Results /archive
segment.target: ResultsUtil /ImportResults /inputfile C:\WAS\Results\JobResultsComputerGUID.xml /db Data Source=localhost\WAS_SQLSERVER;Initial Catalog=RelaxResults;Integrated Security=True /user MyName /project MyProject /testpass Milestone1 /runtag Run1 /tags M1Results /archive

segment.source: Delete a batch of results imported into the database.
segment.target: Delete a batch of results imported into the database.

segment.source: Saves the database configuration file, resultsutil.exe.config, to the same location as the ResultsUtil.
segment.target: Saves the database configuration file, resultsutil.exe.config, to the same location as the ResultsUtil.

segment.source: The database configuration file is prepopulated with the database connections string and user name so that you don’t have to enter it every time that you import results.
segment.target: The database configuration file is prepopulated with the database connections string and user name so that you don’t have to enter it every time that you import results.

segment.source: There is only one database configuration file.
segment.target: There is only one database configuration file.

segment.source: If you have multiple results databases the command-line options will take precedence over the configuration file.
segment.target: If you have multiple results databases the command-line options will take precedence over the configuration file.
